nline asm (several).<br /><br />Arnd cleaned it all up fairly recently.<br /><br />It turns out doing nothing is wrong - not because of architecture<br />issues, but because of compiler issues - and doing inline asms is<br />counter-productive because the compilers will handle the unaligned<br />case for us.<br /><br />So every architecture uses that &lt;asm-generic/unaligned.h&gt; and is happy about it.<br /><br />A couple of architectures still have their own &lt;asm/unaligned.h&gt;, but<br />that's just because they have some additional stuff for legacy reasons<br />there. They still use the generic header for the actual unaligned<br />handling.<br /><br />               Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
